{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d99b99ae-6dec-45f8-a9f2-42191703c85a","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2** / .NET 9, so you have access to the modern patterns.\n\n**Recommended approach:**\n\n- **Constructor** — for sync init + `TestContext` injection\n- **`[TestInitialize]` async method** — for async init\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private HttpClient _client;\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        // Sync init + TestContext injection via constructor\n        _testContext = testContext;\n    }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // Async init\n        _client = await CreateClientAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test...\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_client);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points (MSTest v3+):**\n- `TestContext` is injected via **constructor** — no more `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property.\n- `[TestInitialize]` can return `Task` for async setup.\n- Put sync setup in the constructor, async setup in `[TestInitialize]`.\n- For class-level async init, use `[ClassInitialize]` (static, also supports `Task`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4530c294-41d9-45de-bf99-4e9aaa0536a7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9. In MSTest v3, the recommended way to handle initialization is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: In MSTest v3+, you can inject `TestContext` via constructor (no more need for the static property pattern). Actually, let me think more carefully. MSTest 3.x introduced constructor injection for TestContext. The old pattern was a `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property. The new pattern is constructor injection.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` method or constructor.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` with an async method (returns `Task`).\n\n\n4. **Class-level setup**: `[ClassInitialize]` also supports async methods for one-time initialization across all tests in the class.\n\nI can combine constructor injection with `[TestInitialize]` for flexible per-test setup, whether synchronous or asynchronous.","outputTokens":642,"requestId":"7C19:175BE3:281685C:2C75F0B:69F948CA"},"id":"7a6c15ec-d0d0-4fe7-9a94-5e40c90223df","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:33:11.611Z","parentId":"11dc4ea9-a715-4537-8dc4-be70cd93cc6a"}
